TL;DR Epic rocks and Activision does not care about their communities.

I agree with the beginning sentiment: the chemistry of this trio while discussing eSports is incredible. Definitely subscribed because of that. First time viewing, but if you're interested here's my $0.02. I dont think Call of Duty will ever be as relevant as it once was. I started playing back on CoD4:MW. At that time, like you guys mentioned, the adrenaline of victories was so real. I never minded the adjustments to the game mechanics, because those variations and adjustments kept the newest titles feeling fresh for me. The thing that slayed CoD for me is Activision. Ever since they came up w the model of selling 1/2 a game at the beginning and the other portions separately, those executives have treated the game like a piggy bank rather than an outlet for introverts like myself to really have fun. The amount of involvement and communication between Epic and it's fans is the life-force of this game. Consistent updates (every 1-2 weeks), constant communication during any sort of server related/random issues, and consistently bringing in new content (mini shields, silenced weapons, chug jugs, guided rockets). Not only are they adding the new content, but so far they have done an incredible job of bringing them in almost 100% balanced. Until Activision cares about their community, they will continue to become less relevant. The other main reason I personally enjoy Fortnite is that the game is not a single-element victory. By this, I mean you can be the best shooter in the world, but if you can't build there is a chance you will still get slapped.
